Verse 3. The Originall word here used is 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , which is well translated, What profit: for so the Syriac also reads it, Quae utilitas, filio hominis? What profit is there to the Sonne of man? Aquin. 1. Q. 5. Ar. 6. ad 2m. Now Aquinas tels us, Vtilia dicuntur, quae non habent in se unde desiderentur, sed desiderantur solum ut sunt ducentia in alterum; Things are sayd to be profitable, which have not in themselves any thing for which they be desired, but only are desired as leading to some other thing. And what profit then hath a man of all his worldly labour, which neither in it selfe is to be desired, nor yet to be desired for any other thing?Gregorius Neocaesar: in hunc vers. Wherefore Gregorius Neocaesariensis affirmeth boldly, Nemo est qui utilitatem ullam iis annexam dicere possit, quae homines humi reptantes perficere contendunt, rebus temporariis & caducis addicti;
There is no one who can say, that there is any profit so much as annexed unto those things, which men crawling on the earth, and addicted to vanishing and temporary things doe seeke to performe. This translation doth well answer to the exposition of vanitie which in the former verse I gave. The Arabick doth reade the word, Quae praestantia homini? What excellency is there to a man in all his worldly labour? Wherein doth this make any man to excell another? And therefore Olympiodorus sayth, Quid homine homo amplius habet in eo labore, Olympiodorus in Catena. quod non supra solem, sed laborat sub sole, quando omnes relicta praesenti vita communem mortem subimus? What more then another man hath any man in that labour which he taketh under the Sunne, not above the Sunne, when all leaving this life doe undergoe a common death? The Septuagint doe render it, 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , Quid superest? What remaineth sayth, St. Hierome? Quid amplius habet? What hath he more? saith the Vulgar latine? What remaineth to a man of all his worldly labour? What, besides the vanity whereof the former verse speaketh? For as Hugo de Sancto Victore speaketh, Si secundum aliquid vanum est quod Deus creavit, quomodo non multo magis vanum est quod homo facit? Si temporale est quod fecit aeternuus, quod temporalis facit, quid est? If that bee in some respect vaine, which God hath created, how is not that much more vaine, which man maketh? If that be temporary which he hath made who is eternall, what is that which he maketh, who is himselfe temporary? What hath he more? What more of all his labour, then the labour it selfe, then his labour for his paines? St. Ambrose and St. Aust. doe reade it, Quae abundantia? What abundance is there to a man of all his worldly labour? yea although he be abundant in his labour: yea although it be not only the early labour of the morning, but that labour which endureth the heate of the day, and is under the Sunne: yea although wee consider not only that labour which a man hath taken, or still taketh, but that also which hee shall take (for so the Originall is) even as long as the Sunne is up, and till the Sunne of his life be set, even of all his labour, what great matter, and worthy to bee regarded ariseth from it? The Originall in the Hebrew, and the Greeke word in the Septuagint doe not reject any of these translations. Which he taketh under the Sunne. The Sunne is the master-workman of the world, labouring continually, and labouring under his great master God, to minister unto the inferiour creatures of the world, as the Hebrew name of it 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 doth notifie unto us. Vnder this Master workeman are all other labourers, he calls them up to their labour, he oversees their labour, he appoints unto them their time of ceasing from labour. But although we labour under him, yet unlesse the end of our labour be for something above him, it will not profit us: unlesse as he calls us to labour, so we call upon God for a blessing on our labour,Hugo de Sancto Victore in Ecclesiast. Homil. 1. we shall have no comfort in it. Hugo de Sancto Victore, here by labouring under the Sun, understandeth our labouring under time, because by the motion of the Sun times are distinguished. Whereupon his distinction is, Alia fiunt in tempore
tantum, alia fiunt in tempore & sub tempore, some things are done in time only, some things are done in time and under time: in time onely they are done, which are begun in time, but end not in time: they are done in time, and under time, which begin and end in it. Againe hee saith that of those things which are done under time, Alia fiunt pro tempore, alia fiunt pro aeternitate, some things are done for time, and these are they that yeeld no profit to him that laboureth in them: other things are done for aeternity, and these alone are profitable. As for the rest, whatsoever any one may now deeme of them, yet this speech of Solomons, Cujusvis est animae oratio, quando iis quae hic sunt spoliata, ad vitam quae speratur migraverit, Is the speech of every soule, when being spoiled of those things which are here,Gregor: Nyssenus in Ecclesiast. Hom. 1. she goeth to that life, which is hoped for, as Gregory Nyssene hath it.

Verse 15. It is true, that Gods preservation of all things in the world, in their kindes and natures, though they be passed away and changed, in their particular beings, and individuall existences, doth make that to be now, which hath been before, and that which is to be, to have been already, and God to recall that as it were which is driven away and past, and so the worke of God to abide continually. But I take the Preacher more especially to speake of the workes of Gods providence, and to shew how they are immutable, and doe abide for ever, notwithstanding the fluctuation and inconstancy of worldly things. He tels us therefore here, that with God there is no difference of times to him, that which hath been is now, and it is all one with him to be hereafter, and to have been already. He asketh that (for so the Originall word 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 may well be rendred) which is gone he speaketh to it, as if it were present. For as the Apostle speaketh, Rom. 4.17. He calleth those things which are not, as if they were. And as St. Austin sayth,Augustinus. Non aliter scivit Deus creata quam creanda, God did not know things otherwise when they were created, then he did when they were to be created. But as Boetius Boetius. hath it, Omnia futura praecurrit divinus intuitus, & ad praesentiam revocat, uno{que} ictu simul complectitur, The sight of divine providence outgoeth all future things, and making them to be present, at once doth comprehend them. Wherefore when wee speake of things past, present, and to come, this is not to be understood in respect of God, Sed rerum quae fiunt, & nostri quibus patefiunt, but in respect of the things which are made, and in respect of us to whom they are made knowne. And therefore the manner of speaking in the Scripture, is not that God foreknoweth future things, but that he knoweth them as being present to him. So in St. Iohns Gospel it is sayd of Christ, that he knew all things that should come unto him.
John 18.4. And so God sayth of himselfe, Exod. 3.9. I know that the King of Aegypt will not let you goe. For so according to the Originall it is to be read, although in the booke of Wisedome it be sayd, that God did foreknow it. Wisd. 19.1. It is the saying therefore of Origen, That he is very wicked, who beleeveth not of God, Vt quod nos videmus in praesenti, hoc ille videat in futuro, Origenes. Augustin. That as we see things present, so he seeth things to come. And St. Austin also sayth, God is within every thing, because all things are in him, God is without all things, because all things are under him, God is before all things, because all things were made by him, God is after all things, because all things to him are present before that they are. Now as the being of things when they are, and the certaintie of them that they are, while they are, doth not take away their uncertaintie of being before that they were, nor their mutabilitie either to be or not to be;
So neither doth God in his certaine government of the world, who respecteth all things as present to himselfe, either change the mutable nature of things, or take away the uncertaintie of humane events. And as our beholding of things when they are present doth not alter the instabilitie of their condition, nor the contingency of their being, before that they were; so if there may be any comparison betweene the sight of God and man, the beholding of God, who looketh upon all things as present, doth neither conferre upon him any changeablenesse from the changeablenesse of humane things; nor yet from the immutabilitie of Gods beholding, inferre an immutabilitie in the things of mans life. But if in the difficultie of this point, I have not spoken fully enough, if in the darknesse of it I have not spoken cleerely enough; for the first,Tertull. my hope is, as Tertullian speaketh, Difficilium facilis erit venia, that in hard things a pardon will be easie; for the second, I confesse,Chrysost. as St. Chrysostome speaketh, Sicut multa intelligimus de Deo quae loqui non possumus, ita multa loquimur quae non sumus idonei intelligere, That as wee understand many things of God which we cannot utter, so we utter many things which wee cannot understand.
